args: Non-aggression pact... Trade agreement...\nNone of this should be an issue for the\nChanzelia side, which leaves onlyâ€”
Princess Yelda, do you truly plan to\ninclude THAT condition as well?

They have rejected similar proposals from
two other countries already. If we handle
this poorly, this alliance could collapse
before it even begins.
All the more reason to include it.\nOur backs are against the wall now,\nand this condition is most critical.
I will do whatever it takes to secure the\nfuture of Fadden, and I will brook no\ndiscussion on that point.
...And with that, the trade agreement is\nfinalized between Chanzelia and Fadden.
The final matter is the joint development\nof weaponry. I believe this proposal comes\nfrom the Fadden side?

Indeed it does. As you know, our country
has also been excavating manacastersâ€”
but there is much we could still learn from
you, the eminent pioneers in the field.
I am confused, Princess. I thought you\nstood against the use of such weapons.
Naturally, my ultimate hope is for all\nto live in a world without war.
But I am not naive. I know we must\nhave the power to protect our home\nuntil that day arrives.

Moreover, as both of our countries are 
involved with manacasters, would it not
be best for us to engage in the sharing
of information on the subject?
General Bertrand? I would hear your\nthoughts on this matter.
Hmm... I suppose I have no objections.
Well, so long as the general approves,\nI hereby decree that Fadden's proposal be\nreflected in our agreement in its entirety.
We shall sign the agreement tomorrow.\nAnd with that, discussions are concluded.\nThank you, everyone.
Princess Yelda, might you care to\njoin me for a spot of tea?
Here you are. I have a number of different \nvarieties, so please don't hold back\nif you'd like to sample them all.
You know I cannot stand overly long\nmeetings; they are a waste of everyone's\nprecious time.
If I wish to spend hours dancing around\nan issue, I will host a ball.
To be honest, I was surprised things\nmanaged to wrap up so quickly.
In particular, I had imagined the joint \ndevelopment of manacasters to be more\nof a sticking point.
I understand you rejected proposals from\nboth Svenitla and Barthe to export your \nweapons to them.
Knowing how particular you are about\nthe export of new technologies, I feared\nour proposal might prove a bridge too far.
Ah, but there is a simple explanation:\nWe have more to gain from your proposal\nthan we did from theirs.

For there are currently manacasters being
excavated in your country that we do not
possess ourselves, as well as rare
minerals we can use in their construction.
Even my usually stodgy advisors saw the\nwisdom in the deal. Perhaps I have\neducated them better than I thought!
Although General Bertrand seemed quite\nincensed with you just before the\nmeowting began, did he not?
Any organization needs at least one person\nwilling to push back against the leader.\nWithout that, the center cannot hold.
I've no wish to be surrounded by yes-men.\nRather, I seek counsel only with those\nwho can best serve Chanzelia.

Oh, it's nothing so grand. And yes, while
arms proliferation IS an issue, if we permit
our research to stagnate, someone else
will doubtless surpass us.
We must open our doors to the outside\nand find partners who can help us\ncontinue our development.
Such is how a country must behave in this \nnew age, wouldn't you agree?
It is exactly as you say!
For us it will begin with weapons, but I\npray we can soon work together in\nagriculture, construction, and other fields!
Such a future gets to the very heart\nof our alliance.
I hope this will be the beginning of a\nlong and fruitful relationship.
I as well, Princess Chelle. May both our\nnations prosper for years to come.
Well, with that settled, I believe it's\ntime for a little pre-alliance celebration.\nI think a party is in order!
Thankfully, my dress has been cleaned\nand is ready for use once more.
It is just so easy to dance in...\nPerhaps I should have more made!
I beg your pardon, Princess Chelle,\nbut do you have a moment?
Ah, Leif. How fortuitous of you to come\nwhen I find myself in need of a dance\npartner yet again.
I've not the time for that, Princess;\nI fear I am here to tell you that I do not\nagree with your methods.
You don't wish to attend the party?
I refer to this alliance itself.
Alas, I fear you are too late, dear Leif.\nThere can be no turning back now that\nwe have come this far.
You may wait outside until you\nare sent for.
